    "en": {
      "title": "Sri Lanka crisis would deepen if creditors disagree, IMF says amid China concerns",
      "author": "",
      "body_lines": [
        "ECONOMYNEXT \u2013 Sri Lanka\u2019s ongoing economic crisis would deepen if one creditors disagrees, a senior International Monetary Fund (IMF) official said after announcing a US$2.9 billion reform package amid concerns that China would not go along with Western creditors on debt restructuring on an equal footing.",
        "All Sri Lankan creditors including China have to agree to restructure their existing lending to the island nation before the IMF starts the loan disbursement. Delay in debt restructuring would drag the IMF loan disbursement, Sri Lankan officials who are familiar with the IMF discussions have told the EconomyNext.",
        "China has so far not agreed for debt restructuring which also includes a haircut or writing off some debts. Instead, China has expressed its willingness to refinance Sri Lanka to repay its past loans without any changes, Sri Lankan officials say.",
        "\u201cIf one creditor or creditors are not willing to provide these assurances, that would indeed deepen the crisis here in Sri Lanka and would undermine the repayment capacity,\u201d Peter Breuer, senior IMF mission chief told reporters in Colombo when asked what if China does not agree on a debt restructuring plan.",
        "\u201cSo a deepening crisis means that essentially the resources available to service the debt would become less,\u201d he said at the media briefing after concluding a nine-day visit to finalize the staff-level agreement and possible loan package for Sri Lanka\u2019s reforms.",
        "\u201cSo it is actually in the interest of all creditors to collaborate together and with Sri Lanka so that Sri Lanka can emerge from this crisis as quickly as possible and regain its repayment capacity and service this new debt that will come out of these debt negotiations.\u201d",
        "Sri Lanka has already hired leading financial and legal advisory firms Lazard and Clifford Chance LLP to support its debt restructuring as the country is on the brink of bankruptcy. Lazard has been the legal advisor in Zambia\u2019s debt restructuring with the South African nation\u2019s creditor\u2019s including China.",
        "Unlike with members in Paris Club, the IMF is unable to deal with China as it is not in the Paris Club, which formed by a group of creditors who provide debt treatments to debtor countries in the form of rescheduling, by postponement or, in the case of concessional rescheduling, reduction in debt service obligations during a defined period.",
        "\u201cSri Lanka is in a special situation that much of its official debt is outside of Paris Club creditors,\u201d Breuer said.",
        "\u201cIn the case of Sri Lanka, it owed to creditors that are not owed to Paris Club. It is important to move expeditiously. We want to avoid the crisis from becoming worse.\u201d (Colombo/Sept01/2022)"
      ],
